{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014sv5JCfXXyfchPXizPdzRT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need to write the migration plan. Let me summarize what I've found:\n\n**Current State:**\n- RabbitMQ version: 3.12.14 (out of support)\n- Erlang/OTP: 25 (25.3.2.15)\n- Image: rabbitmq:3.12-management\n- Cluster: 3 nodes (rabbitmq-0, rabbitmq-1, rabbitmq-2), all disk nodes, all running, no partitions, no alarms, no maintenance\n\n**Virtual Hosts:**\n- `/` (default)\n- `/app`\n\n**Users:**\n- `admin` with administrator privileges\n- `app-user` as a regular user\n\n**Permissions and Configuration:**\n- Both vhosts have admin with full permissions; app-user has full access to `/app`\n- One classic durable queue (`app-queue`) exists on `/app`, no queues on the default vhost\n- No policies are configured, but all feature flags are enabled including quorum and stream queue support\n\n**Current Issues and Upgrade Strategy:**\nRabbitMQ 3.12.14 is out of support and lacks HA policies for the classic queue. I need to plan a staged upgrade through 3.13 and 4.x versions with rolling restarts, while also converting the classic queue to a quorum queue for better high availability since the infrastructure already supports it.\n\n**Queue Migration Approach:**\nSince classic queues can't be converted in-place to quorum queues, I'll need to create a new quorum queue, migrate producers and consumers to it, then drain and remove the old classic queue. This ensures zero downtime during the transition.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2052,"cache_read_input_tokens":32768,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2052},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_u